    <stitle>REYCO 101A, 102, 102W SUSPENSIONS - LOAD EQUALIZATION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="4">
        <title>LOAD EQUALIZATION</title>
        <para>Substantial changes in fifth wheel location or suspension load will affect equal load distribution between
            the axles. Equal load distribution is obtained by installing spacers between the leaf spring assemblies and
            the axle housings.
        </para>
        <para>Check load distribution as follows:</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If vehicle is equipped with an adjustable fifth wheel, place fifth wheel in normal operating
                location.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On vehicles equipped with Dayton four-spring suspension, the upper torque rods must be
                disconnected before weight measurements are taken.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply a load to the suspension equal in capacity to the load the suspension will normally be
                carrying.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>Avoid the use of a full platform scale. Use only a single axle or tandem axle scale. Make sure
                        the scale is level when taking weight reading.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The proper method to be used when weighing the forward or rear rear axle using a tandem
                scale is illustrated in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300508">Figure 8</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300509">Figure 9</hotlnk>. When weighing the forward rear axle, the flat portion of
                the tire tread of the rear rear axle should be just at the edge of the scale as shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300508">Figure 8</hotlnk>.To weigh the rear rear axle, the flat portion of the tire
                tread of the forward rear axle should just be at the opposite edge of the scale as shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300509">Figure 9</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0300508" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0300508" filename="../figg03/G0300508.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 8. Forward Axle Weighting</caption>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f0300509" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0300509" filename="../figg03/G0300509.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 9. Rear Axle Weighting</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Weigh forward rear and rear rear axle individually and record weights. When placing vehicle
                on scale, bring vehicle to an easy stop using trailer brakes only.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Equalize weight differences in forward rear axle and rear rear axle by installing spacers
                between the leaf spring assemblies and the axle housings. If the tandem axle can be adjusted to within
                500 lbs. (227 kg.), it generally is acceptable. Spacers must be installed on both sides of the lighter
                axle. Use the charts shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300510">Figure 10</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300511">Figure 11</hotlnk>to determine the amount of spacers required and at which
                axle the spacers should be installed. Do not use more than two spacers of any combination per side.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0300510" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0300510" filename="../figg03/G0300510.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Load Equalization Chart</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0300511" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0300511" filename="../figg03/G0300511.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Load Equalization Chart</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>Example:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Forward rear axle 1100 lbs. heavier. Use 1/2 inch (.50) spacer under rear rear axle.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rear rear axle 1800 lbs. heavier. Use 3/4 inch (.75) spacer under forward rear axle.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On vehicles equipped with Dayton four-spring suspension, it will be necessary to check the
                upper torque rod adjustment after completing the load equalization procedure.
            </para>
        </step1>
